<tr>
<td width=50%><font color=white>Posted By: Gartha</font></td><td width=50% align=right><font color=white>2000-07-05 01:33:50</font></td></tr><tr>
<td colspan=2 bgcolor="#0000AF"><font color=white>The reason you cannot dual wield this weapon has nothing to do with it's ass-kickingness as a weapon.  Items are Lore when they are supposed to be a "unique" item, only one of a kind, but since so many people play the game, it would be unfair to have truly unique (and thus unattainable once found by somebody else) items.  The item is No Drop because it's an asswhupper, and they don't want twinkies running around with this.  Not that you can't get around the anti-twinking restrictions, but you have to work at it.  Basically, dual wielding a Lore sword would be like dual wielding Excalibur.  You can't.  There is only one.  BUT, and it's a big but, in the name of customer happiness, your buddy can have one too.  Think about how joyous everybody would be if there was just one Oracle Robe, just one Bullsmasher, just one Trueshot.  Now do you see why it is that some of these wonderful items are Lore?</font></td></tr></table>
<BR>
<table width=100%>
<tr>
<td width=50%><font color=white>Posted By: Isgrimur</font></td><td width=50% align=right><font color=white>2000-07-06 11:39:31</font></td></tr><tr>
<td colspan=2 bgcolor="#0000AF"><font color=white>Add to Above Post:  Both Lore and No-Drop are actions taken by Verant because of the FARMING that took place in the early days of EQ.  A No-Drop item cannot be farmed at all.  A Lore item makes it harder as you must A) sell the item prior to looting another or B) dump it off on a mule character.  Both of these options takes time and trouble.  Prevents high level characters from hunting / camping a mob for 12 hours straight and leaving with a Pack full of (fill in the blank) to sell at the next bazaar.  Lore / No-Drop was a necessary action.  It has not eliminated Farming but it has decreased it greatly.</font></td></tr></table>
